WEBVTT

00:14.101 --> 00:15.667
<i>
What comes to mind</i>

00:15.798 --> 00:18.366
<i>when you hear
the words Iran-Contra? </i>

00:18.496 --> 00:20.846
<i>The hearing
will please come to order. </i>

00:20.977 --> 00:22.892
<i>You may remember
a charismatic marine. </i>

00:25.416 --> 00:28.724
As you all know by now,
my name is Oliver North,

00:28.854 --> 00:31.074
lieutenant colonel,
United States Marine Corps.

00:31.205 --> 00:34.121
<i>Or an outcry about missiles
being sold to Iran. </i>

00:34.991 --> 00:36.862
Is it possible

00:36.993 --> 00:38.647
that fired White House
official Oliver North

00:38.777 --> 00:41.258
could have diverted profits
from Iran arms sales

00:41.389 --> 00:42.912
<i>to the Contras on his own?</i>

00:43.043 --> 00:44.870
<i>Maybe you recall
the funding of a covert war </i>

00:45.001 --> 00:46.133
<i>in Central America.</i>

00:48.657 --> 00:50.311
<i>It's a messy story</i>

00:50.441 --> 00:53.401
<i>that spanned
multiple continents, </i>

00:53.531 --> 00:57.013
<i>and it all started
in an office like this one. </i>

00:57.144 --> 01:00.364
<i>It was this tapestry
of intrigue. </i>

01:00.495 --> 01:02.410
<i>Every day
there was a surprise. </i>

01:02.540 --> 01:06.718
It was so outlandish.

01:06.849 --> 01:10.418
The first I heard about it,
I really couldn't believe it.

01:13.160 --> 01:15.771
<i>Perhaps because
of its complexity, </i>

01:15.901 --> 01:18.861
<i>Iran-Contra, unlike
other presidential scandals, </i>

01:18.991 --> 01:22.604
<i>barely left a mark
on our collective memory. </i>

01:22.734 --> 01:24.171
Watergate
was really easy-peasy

01:24.301 --> 01:26.260
compared to this.

01:26.390 --> 01:27.783
You didn't have to go to Iran.

01:27.913 --> 01:28.914
You didn't have to go
to Central America.

01:29.045 --> 01:31.221
The Sultan of Brunei
wasn't involved.

01:33.528 --> 01:35.965
It was far more sophisticated,
complex,

01:36.096 --> 01:39.360
and frankly scarier--
far scarier than Watergate.

01:39.490 --> 01:41.405
Why was it conducted
with such secrecy,

01:41.536 --> 01:42.493
and why were we all
kept in the dark

01:42.624 --> 01:43.886
for such a long period
of time?

01:46.758 --> 01:49.413
This was not low stakes.

01:49.544 --> 01:52.503
This was high stakes
on the world stage.

01:52.634 --> 01:55.071
<i>I think,
if you break down </i>

01:55.202 --> 01:57.465
<i>the whole scandal
piece by piece, </i>

01:57.595 --> 02:00.337
<i>a single clarifying theme
comes into focus. </i>

02:00.468 --> 02:03.123
We did not--repeat--did not

02:03.253 --> 02:07.039
trade weapons or anything else
for hostages.

02:07.170 --> 02:11.609
<i>Iran-Contra
is a story about hostages-- </i>

02:11.740 --> 02:14.351
<i>those who take them,
those who rescue them, </i>

02:14.482 --> 02:17.441
<i>and those who become
hostages themselves. </i>

02:17.572 --> 02:21.967
Any kind of hostage situation
creates a huge dilemma.

02:22.098 --> 02:25.536
It is a power game,
and the hostage taker

02:25.667 --> 02:27.495
largely controls
the situation,

02:27.625 --> 02:30.933
but it's also a challenge
you can't walk away from.

02:31.063 --> 02:33.501
You better make damn sure

02:33.631 --> 02:36.939
that you have looked
at every consequence,

02:37.069 --> 02:39.333
looked at
every possible nuance...

02:41.073 --> 02:43.598
Because once you give in
to a ransom,

02:43.728 --> 02:46.209
there is no stop.

02:48.864 --> 02:51.345
<i>I'm Leon Neyfakh.</i>

02:51.475 --> 02:54.913
<i>This is "Fiasco,"</i>

02:55.044 --> 02:57.307
<i>the story of Iran-Contra.</i>

03:05.359 --> 03:09.450
<i>While Iran-Contra is known
as Ronald Reagan's scandal, </i>

03:09.580 --> 03:10.842
<i>the stage was set
years earlier </i>

03:10.973 --> 03:12.279
<i>by a different president.</i>

03:17.153 --> 03:18.546
It's a long way
from Plains, Georgia,

03:18.676 --> 03:21.157
to Washington D.C.

03:21.288 --> 03:23.464
The strength of a person
can be measured

03:23.594 --> 03:26.467
by the path he takes
to travel there.

03:26.597 --> 03:28.382
For Jimmy Carter,
that road was one of hard work

03:28.512 --> 03:30.427
and determination.

03:30.558 --> 03:33.038
<i>This was the 1976
presidential campaign. </i>

03:36.564 --> 03:38.479
I heard he was
a peanut farmer.

03:40.524 --> 03:41.917
<i>Jimmy Carter
entered the race </i>

03:42.047 --> 03:43.875
<i>as a Washington outsider</i>

03:44.006 --> 03:45.921
<i>seeking an end
to the Nixonian era </i>

03:46.051 --> 03:48.010
<i>in American politics.</i>

03:48.140 --> 03:49.533
Hey, I'll go to your church
next Sunday, okay?

03:51.231 --> 03:53.058
<i>He was a man of faith.</i>

03:53.189 --> 03:54.843
<i>He wanted to advance
a human rights agenda </i>

03:54.973 --> 03:56.453
<i>across the world.</i>

03:56.584 --> 04:00.544
He is a genuine
moral beacon

04:00.675 --> 04:03.721
capable of making people
believe in something.

04:03.852 --> 04:05.375
He was the real thing.

04:07.638 --> 04:09.597
I just think
he's a very neat man.

04:09.727 --> 04:11.860
You got me, all right.

04:11.990 --> 04:14.123
I picture him
like one of us--

04:14.254 --> 04:15.429
one of the working people,
one of the common people.

04:22.566 --> 04:24.525
Jimmy Carter comes in

04:24.655 --> 04:28.920
promising to bring America
back to its best self.

04:29.051 --> 04:31.488
His number one campaign promise
in 1976

04:31.619 --> 04:33.447
was "I will not lie to you."

04:36.580 --> 04:37.973
We want Jimmy!

04:38.103 --> 04:40.454
We want Jimmy!
We want Jimmy!

04:40.584 --> 04:43.195
We want Jimmy!

04:43.326 --> 04:46.503
There's a new mood
in America.

04:46.634 --> 04:51.987
We've been shaken
by a tragic war abroad

04:52.117 --> 04:55.251
and by scandals
and broken promises at home.

04:55.382 --> 04:58.820
Our people are searching
for new voices

04:58.950 --> 05:01.475
and new ideas and new leaders.

05:03.433 --> 05:06.958
It was after our defeat
in the Vietnam War.

05:07.089 --> 05:09.613
It was after
the Watergate scandal.

05:09.744 --> 05:13.530
Jimmy Carter was elected
as a man who was supposed

05:13.661 --> 05:15.576
to be the antithesis
of all those things.

05:17.317 --> 05:19.710
It's now a time for healing.

05:19.841 --> 05:22.583
We wanna have faith again.

05:22.713 --> 05:24.672
We want to be proud again.

05:24.802 --> 05:27.022
We just want the truth again.

05:27.152 --> 05:28.676
It's time for the people
to run the government

05:28.806 --> 05:30.678
and not the other way around!

05:36.727 --> 05:39.687
He set out to change things,

05:39.817 --> 05:42.037
and he was a social engineer,

05:42.167 --> 05:44.431
and one of the things
that he wanted to do

05:44.561 --> 05:45.867
was create peace.

05:57.357 --> 05:59.097
<i>Election night</i>

05:59.228 --> 06:01.448
<i>from CBS News
Election Headquarters </i>

06:01.578 --> 06:02.927
<i>in New York.</i>

06:03.058 --> 06:05.408
Shortly before dawn,
Jimmy Carter reached

06:05.539 --> 06:09.020
the end of his improbable
two-year, half-million-mile

06:09.151 --> 06:11.545
political quest
and won the presidency.

06:16.158 --> 06:18.203
Remains to be seen
whether his politics

06:18.334 --> 06:21.685
of love and trust
and sweeping promises

06:21.816 --> 06:24.340
could capture a country
which has had reason

06:24.471 --> 06:26.516
to become mistrustful
of politicians.

06:35.351 --> 06:37.875
<i>Not long into
Carter's term, it became clear </i>

06:38.006 --> 06:39.964
<i>that he couldn't
just turn everything around </i>

06:40.095 --> 06:41.096
<i>like his campaign ads
had promised. </i>

06:43.794 --> 06:45.709
<i>The country
was being battered. </i>

06:45.840 --> 06:48.538
There is growing concern
about the general health

06:48.669 --> 06:51.628
of the American economy.

06:51.759 --> 06:53.717
<i>There were some
really big problems, </i>

06:53.848 --> 06:56.677
<i>and none of them
had simple solutions. </i>

06:56.807 --> 06:58.722
It's a profound change
that the American economy

06:58.853 --> 07:00.985
is undergoing,
a change with a name--

07:01.116 --> 07:02.596
deindustrialization.

07:05.120 --> 07:07.209
1979 in particular,

07:07.339 --> 07:08.689
average incomes
begin to decline,

07:08.819 --> 07:11.039
manufacturing jobs
in the United States

07:11.169 --> 07:13.998
begin to really
start tailing off,

07:14.129 --> 07:16.218
and people would say things
like, you know,

07:16.348 --> 07:17.915
"Well, my father certainly
didn't have to put up

07:18.046 --> 07:19.787
with this kind of crap."

07:19.917 --> 07:22.659
And, you know,
"My steel factory just closed,

07:22.790 --> 07:24.139
and now here I am
standing in line for gas."

07:27.447 --> 07:29.753
<i>The oil shortage of 1979</i>

07:29.884 --> 07:32.016
<i>forced Americans
to wake up before dawn </i>

07:32.147 --> 07:33.235
<i>just to fill up their tanks.</i>

07:36.151 --> 07:37.761
I'm all out.
Not a drop.

07:37.892 --> 07:39.502
How about five dollars?
That's it.

07:39.633 --> 07:41.243
Anger
and bewilderment are growing

07:41.373 --> 07:43.114
as more and more Americans
cope with gasoline lines

07:43.245 --> 07:45.160
and empty pumps.

07:45.290 --> 07:46.509
I have to be at work at00.

07:48.468 --> 07:50.252
For millions of Americans,

07:50.382 --> 07:51.993
this may be the worst weekend
they've ever faced

07:52.123 --> 07:54.169
for finding gasoline
to give them

07:54.299 --> 07:56.650
the automobile freedom
they take as their due.

07:56.780 --> 07:58.086
I'm in a line
two hours here,

07:58.216 --> 07:59.304
and I can't get gas.

07:59.435 --> 08:00.958
This is baloney.

08:03.874 --> 08:05.528
Carter doesn't get my vote
next year.

08:09.053 --> 08:12.317
<i>In July of 1979,
Carter did something </i>

08:12.448 --> 08:14.929
<i>politicians hardly ever do.</i>

08:15.059 --> 08:17.584
<i>He admitted to the voters
that good times </i>

08:17.714 --> 08:20.064
<i>were not around the corner,
and that the order of the day </i>

08:20.195 --> 08:21.979
<i>wasn't hope,
but self-sacrifice. </i>

08:24.416 --> 08:27.115
<i>It's clear
that the true problems </i>

08:27.245 --> 08:30.727
<i>of our nation are much deeper</i>

08:30.858 --> 08:33.164
than gasoline lines
or energy shortages,

08:33.295 --> 08:35.776
deeper even
than inflation or recession.

08:38.387 --> 08:41.216
<i>It is a crisis of confidence.</i>

08:43.131 --> 08:45.960
We can see this crisis
in the growing doubt

08:46.090 --> 08:48.484
about the meaning
of our own lives

08:48.615 --> 08:51.095
and in the loss
of a unity of purpose

08:51.226 --> 08:52.706
for our nation.

08:54.664 --> 08:57.928
The erosion of our confidence
in the future

08:58.059 --> 08:59.451
is threatening to destroy

08:59.582 --> 09:02.324
the social
and the political fabric

09:02.454 --> 09:04.718
of America.

09:04.848 --> 09:06.458
His advice
to the American people

09:06.589 --> 09:08.504
in his famous
"Crisis of Confidence" speech

09:08.635 --> 09:11.463
was that we have
to make do with less.

09:11.594 --> 09:14.249
We've lived too well,
and now we're paying the bill.

09:14.379 --> 09:19.210
<i>This is not a message
of happiness or reassurance, </i>

09:19.341 --> 09:21.735
<i>but it is the truth,</i>

09:21.865 --> 09:23.171
<i>and it is a warning.</i>

09:26.957 --> 09:30.221
I still think
he's a peanut farmer,

09:30.352 --> 09:31.701
and he don't know
how to run this country.

09:31.832 --> 09:32.746
Believe it.

09:34.530 --> 09:36.663
<i>Carter's hard truths
did not sit well </i>

09:36.793 --> 09:37.359
<i>with everyone.</i>

09:40.014 --> 09:40.797
Do you feel
that President Carter

09:40.928 --> 09:42.059
has been a good leader?

09:44.453 --> 09:46.324
No, I don't.

09:46.455 --> 09:47.891
I can't put my finger on it,

09:48.022 --> 09:49.414
but there's just something
he doesn't have.

09:52.026 --> 09:55.464
God has something
much better for everyone.

09:55.595 --> 09:57.858
<i>Some Americans
wanted a different answer. </i>

10:00.295 --> 10:01.775
<i>And if they switched
on their TV set </i>

10:01.905 --> 10:02.732
<i>on Sunday morning...</i>

10:02.863 --> 10:04.386
Ready.

10:04.516 --> 10:05.866
Baptist Church
in Lynchburg, Virginia.

10:05.996 --> 10:07.650
<i>...there was one
waiting for them </i>

10:07.781 --> 10:10.871
<i>in the form of a TV preacher
named Jerry Falwell. </i>

10:11.001 --> 10:12.873
Let's lead the way,
and under God,

10:13.003 --> 10:14.091
let's turn our country around.

10:14.222 --> 10:16.877
<i>The sense among Americans</i>

10:17.007 --> 10:19.053
<i>that things had gotten
fundamentally off track </i>

10:19.183 --> 10:21.316
went hand-in-hand
with the revival

10:21.446 --> 10:22.752
of religious feeling
in the United States.

10:24.406 --> 10:26.408
If America survives
this decade,

10:26.538 --> 10:27.452
it will be because
we experienced

10:27.583 --> 10:29.324
a spiritual awakening.

10:29.454 --> 10:31.239
My name is Ralph Reed,

10:31.369 --> 10:33.807
and I was a leader
of the Christian Coalition.

10:35.504 --> 10:38.376
I was a young person,
really lost spiritually.

10:38.507 --> 10:41.641
I opened up the Yellow Pages,
went to "Evangelical,"

10:41.771 --> 10:44.208
put my finger on a church,
and I walked in,

10:44.339 --> 10:46.123
and I sat in a pew,

10:46.254 --> 10:48.865
and the pastor turned around
to the organist,

10:48.996 --> 10:51.955
and he said,
"Stop the music."

10:52.086 --> 10:55.219
And he said,
"I don't know who you are.

10:55.350 --> 10:57.961
I don't know how you got here."

10:58.092 --> 11:01.225
He said, "But I want you
to know that today

11:01.356 --> 11:03.271
is your day of salvation."

11:07.231 --> 11:09.364
And Jerry Falwell,
I got to know him,

11:09.494 --> 11:12.628
and he is such
an important historic figure

11:12.759 --> 11:16.458
because he ushered
fundamentalists

11:16.588 --> 11:20.723
back into the mainstream
of American life,

11:20.854 --> 11:23.160
which is something that they
had been withdrawn from

11:23.291 --> 11:25.946
for many, many decades.

11:26.076 --> 11:28.383
<i>Falwell was part
of a new movement </i>

11:28.513 --> 11:30.602
<i>of televangelists
who offered Americans </i>

11:30.733 --> 11:33.649
<i>something precious,
a chance to be saved </i>

11:33.780 --> 11:35.912
<i>without ever leaving
their couch. </i>

11:38.828 --> 11:41.048
I want us to bow our heads
and close our eyes

11:41.178 --> 11:45.008
across this building,
there by television set.

11:45.139 --> 11:47.358
You know, Falwell had
"The Old Time Gospel Hour"

11:47.489 --> 11:49.926
and was seen
by millions of people.

11:54.061 --> 11:56.672
Those of you watching
by the television set,

11:56.803 --> 11:59.501
will you right now confess,
"Oh, God, I'm a sinner."

11:59.631 --> 12:01.590
And then write me and ask
for a free copy of my booklet,

12:01.721 --> 12:04.071
"How To Get Started Right."

12:04.201 --> 12:06.551
Literally, hundreds
of millions of dollars

12:06.682 --> 12:08.597
were being raised.

12:08.728 --> 12:10.991
Jerry Falwell built schools.

12:11.121 --> 12:13.297
He built a whole
social welfare system

12:13.428 --> 12:14.298
for his church members.

12:14.429 --> 12:16.605
You can say, "Bible."

12:16.736 --> 12:19.564
He had a TV empire.
He had a radio empire.

12:25.309 --> 12:27.224
It was this
all-encompassing culture

12:27.355 --> 12:29.444
in which one could kind of
live one's entire life

12:29.574 --> 12:30.140
in this kind of bubble.

12:32.055 --> 12:34.188
<i>By 1979,</i>

12:34.318 --> 12:38.670
<i>nearly a third of Americans
identified as evangelical. </i>

12:38.801 --> 12:41.456
Thank God that the parents
of these children

12:41.586 --> 12:45.460
didn't believe in abortion,
or they wouldn't be here.

12:45.590 --> 12:48.071
There was a view
in the late '70s

12:48.202 --> 12:50.378
that America
was in moral decline,

12:50.508 --> 12:54.164
and America, to us,
looked weak,

12:54.295 --> 12:57.211
and then I think a final thing
was profound disappointment

12:57.341 --> 12:59.517
with Jimmy Carter
and his presidency.

12:59.648 --> 13:01.389
One of the ironies
of this entire history

13:01.519 --> 13:03.217
was that Jimmy Carter

13:03.347 --> 13:04.784
was the first
presidential candidate

13:04.914 --> 13:08.396
who was a out and proud
evangelical Christian.

13:08.526 --> 13:10.572
But, again, he was, you know,
the old-fashioned kind

13:10.702 --> 13:13.923
of evangelical Christian
who kept his religious views

13:14.054 --> 13:14.968
out of his policy decisions.

13:15.098 --> 13:17.492
I see...

13:17.622 --> 13:19.407
the political situation

13:19.537 --> 13:22.149
and the military situation

13:22.279 --> 13:25.413
and the economic situation
and the energy problem.

13:25.543 --> 13:29.373
I see all of these
as crises that are pressing

13:29.504 --> 13:32.420
this planet towards a climax.

13:32.550 --> 13:35.075
<i>Falwell was tapping into
a sense that America </i>

13:35.205 --> 13:35.684
<i>was changing,
and that something </i>

13:35.815 --> 13:38.121
<i>had already been lost.</i>

13:38.252 --> 13:40.297
<i>He began to build
not just a religious movement, </i>

13:40.428 --> 13:42.038
<i>but a political one.</i>

13:42.169 --> 13:43.213
Right here in Washington,

13:43.344 --> 13:45.825
this city has become
as corrupt

13:45.955 --> 13:48.001
as any of the cities
in the Old Testament

13:48.131 --> 13:49.741
which God destroyed,

13:49.872 --> 13:53.702
and I think that unless we
have a fundamental change,

13:53.833 --> 13:55.312
I think this country
will be destroyed as well.

13:59.229 --> 14:01.057
<i>Jimmy Carter
wasn't just facing </i>

14:01.188 --> 14:02.319
<i>a changing landscape
on the home front. </i>

14:09.283 --> 14:12.547
<i>In 1979, it seemed
the whole world </i>

14:12.677 --> 14:15.071
<i>was going through
a transformative convulsion. </i>

14:15.202 --> 14:17.030
This is a day
when every nation is claiming

14:17.160 --> 14:18.205
its own identity.

14:20.120 --> 14:22.252
<i>That included Iran,</i>

14:22.383 --> 14:24.733
<i>America's most important ally
in the Middle East. </i>

14:34.830 --> 14:37.441
<i>In 1979, Iranians were looking</i>

14:37.572 --> 14:40.531
<i>to redefine
their national identity. </i>

14:40.662 --> 14:42.620
<i>For years, the country
had been caught </i>

14:42.751 --> 14:44.709
<i>in the middle
of an ideological battle </i>

14:44.840 --> 14:46.276
<i>between Soviet
and Western influence. </i>

15:00.682 --> 15:02.771
<i>After months of unrest...</i>

15:05.817 --> 15:08.733
<i>...Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi,
Iran's monarch, </i>

15:08.864 --> 15:10.344
<i>fled the country.</i>

15:13.913 --> 15:17.220
<i>America had been a friend
of the shah for years. </i>

15:17.351 --> 15:19.744
<i>Now that Iran was
no longer under his control, </i>

15:19.875 --> 15:22.312
<i>an uneasy
power vacuum prevailed, </i>

15:22.443 --> 15:26.751
<i>and Jimmy Carter found himself
in a delicate position. </i>

15:26.882 --> 15:29.015
The situation in Iran now,
politically speaking,

15:29.145 --> 15:32.409
is very sensitive.

15:32.540 --> 15:34.324
We do not have any intention
of interfering

15:34.455 --> 15:35.760
in the affairs of Iran,

15:35.891 --> 15:37.458
the internal affairs
of their government,

15:37.588 --> 15:39.112
and we don't want
any other country

15:39.242 --> 15:40.287
to do it either.

15:42.463 --> 15:45.945
<i>But as 1979 drew to a close,</i>

15:46.075 --> 15:48.425
<i>Carter unintentionally tripped
a live wire </i>

15:48.556 --> 15:50.601
<i>when he welcomed the shah
into the United States. </i>

